data <- read.csv('IBM_data.csv')

Data cleaning

In order for us to visualize and model data, data frame has to have clean names, be consistent, not include any NA values and not redundant. The data quality was improved by using clean_names function, that standardizes column names and removing columns that do not hold any value for this research. That includes:

  • employee count, that corresponds to index of the data frame;
  • over18, all employees in this data frame are over 18 years old, the data does not hold any necessary information;
  • standard hours are equal to 80 hour for every employee;
  • performance rating ranges only from 3 to 4 and is not representative, since every one in the company seems to perform on a similar level.
#cleaning the names
data <- data %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  select(-employee_count, -over18, -standard_hours, -performance_rating) 

data_attrition_yes <- data %>%
  filter(attrition == "Yes")

data_attrition_no <- data %>%
  filter(attrition == "No")

Skimming through our dataset, we have these variables type:

  • Numeric variables:
    • Related to personal information: age, distance_from_home, employee_number (id variable)
    • Related to income: hourly_rate, daily_rate, monthly_rate, monthly_income, percent_salary_hike
    • Related to time in company: years_at_company, years_in_current_role, years_since_last_promotion, years_with_curr_manager, total_working_years
    • other: num_companies_worked, standard_hours(to delete), training_times_last_year, employee_count (to delete)
  • Categorical variables:
    • Binary variables: attrition(target variable), gender, over18 (to delete), over_time
    • Nominal variables: department, education_field, job_role, marital_status
    • Ordinal variables:
      • Ordinal regarding satisfaction and performance : environment_satisfaction, job_satisfaction, relationship_satisfaction, work_life_balance,job_involvement,performance_rating
      • Other ordinal: business_travel, education, job_level, stock_option_level

Explanation for some variables:

  • Relationship satisfaction = how happy is the employee with her colleagues.
  • Employee count is almost useless since it repeats itself. Employee number is the most important since it is the Unique identifier i.e Primary Key
  • Work Life Balance: 1-5, 1 is least balance 5 is most balance

Question of topic: What is attrition

Attrition: It is basically the turnover rate of employees inside an organization.

Attrition in our data set is recorded as Yes/No. Yes is when the employees leave the company and No is otherwise.

This can happen for many reasons:

  • Employees looking for better opportunities.
  • A negative working environment.
  • Bad management
  • Sickness of an employee (or even death)
  • Excessive working hours

Turnover has negative consequence for a company, since companys resources have to be spend on finding employees replacements. And depending on the job role, the costs associated with hiring can be very high, especially for more complicated executive position, as the level of uncertainty is attached to criteria of choosing any particular candidate. Hiring costs are noticeably lower for job positions where job scope defines easier and criteria for candidates is very clear.

IBM is a technology corporation, therefore, there are plethora of job position that require a very specific set of skills, level of education and work experience, where the costs of losing an employee is high. It is in companys interest to decrease hiring costs.

Researching and modelling attrition can be one of the ways to reduce IBM turnover rate. Not only will we be able to understand companys problem zones when it comes to turnover, but we also will able to predict employees attrition. That information can help HR department make data driven decisions and build new strategy for reducing turnover rate, helping company retain competent employees and reduce HR costs.

We found a few interesting points about the employees that leave the company:

  • Most of them are in their 20s and 30s, with 30s leading the chart. Kapphahn (2017) shares that young employees tend to jump jobs for higher turnover and to seek meaningfulness in their job. The statistics pointed out that young employees are willing to switch to higher paying jobs, jobs that would lead to long-term career development, and jobs that give them the feeling of impactful or meaningful.

  • In terms of marital status, attrition is the highest for the single group. Linking with age group, young people has higher chance to stay single. Moreover, the global marital age also increase for both genders due to many personal reasons, such as education, career advancement, personal choice, etc. So we will see most of our young employees are single. More to speak, single employees are relatively easier to make the attrition decision when compared to their fellow married colleagues. Being single, they do not have to worry about their dependents but only for themselves, so the bargaining scale has less item to be considered.

  • Regard to education, bachelor level has the highest attrition rate, followed by master and college level. Gender, in this case, has no signification between the 2 genders in terms of attrition.

  • Oddly enough, employees with level 3 of relationship satisfaction (on a 1-4 scale with 4 being most satisfactory) has the highest attrition rate, followed by level 4. Amongst the employees that leave, most of them have worked at between 2 to 5 companies.

How work and work travel affects the attrition?

Among the variables in the dataset, we classify business travel, distance from home, job role, overtime, and work life balance as employees work travels.

  • Business travel

In travel frequent category, almost 30% of people who decided to quit traveled frequently, in comparison to only 17% of those who stayed travel frequently. So the percentage of people who committed to quit and those who did not, almost doubles in frequent travelers. That leads to a conclusion that frequency of business travel does affect the attrition.

  • Work life balance vs distance from home

This box plot showcases the distribution of distance from work to home by work life balance, where 1 is the worst work life balance and 4 is the best. We can see that people who decided to quit, if they rate their work life balance lower than 4, they also usually live further away from work. The distance from home is more evenly distributed in people who stayed, the box plot with positive attrition is less homogeneous. While people who are very satisfied with work-life balance live the same distance from work, as the ones who dint quit, majority of people who rate their work-life balance lower than 4 tend to live further away from work. That leads to a conclusion that distance from home does affect the work life balance and attrition, as those who live further from their offices, spend more time on daily travels.

Looking at a data from IBM, a conclusion can be made that younger people tend to leave more often in comparison to other age groups. As age increases, the percentage of people who quit their job decreases drastically. Young employee, who is single and has a lower monthly income is more likely to quit in comparison to other groups. And employees before their 50s, who are not single and have higher salary are less likely to start looking for a job somewhere else or retire. There is an increase in percentage of positive attrition starting at age 50 that can be connected to the age of employee.

The profile of a worker which is the most like to churn:

  1. Young

  2. Low salary

  3. Working overtime

  4. Single

  5. Working as a sales rep or a lab tech

  6. Has a low overall satisfaction level

  7. Travels frequently

Lets move on to build our model

Modelling

Setting the dataset

Based on the findings of our exploratory analysis, we found that there are only certain variables that are significant for our model in predicting employees attrition. So we will prepare our working dataset:

data_model <- data %>% select(attrition, monthly_income, over_time, 
                              job_role, job_level, age,environment_satisfaction, 
                              marital_status, relationship_satisfaction,  
                              years_since_last_promotion, department, business_travel,
                              job_involvement, job_satisfaction, 
                              work_life_balance, num_companies_worked, distance_from_home) %>% 
                        mutate_if(is.character,factor)

Preprocessing

We split our data into training and testing. Training set will be used for model learning and test will be used for fitting and making predictions. Before splitting the model, set.seed was added. As initial_split uses random splitting of the data, we have to makes sure that for the research purposes the split is the same every time we run the code. In this research the bootstrap method will also be used. Bootstrap is a resampling method, where the data set is divide into equal size samples and are repeatedly drawn.

set.seed(2021)

split <- initial_split(data_model)

train <- training(split)

test <- testing(split)

folds <- bootstraps(train, strata = attrition)

Lets build our models:

Build Logistic regression model

Logistic regression is one of the ways to model a binomial outcome (yes or no outcomes). The model uses a regression analysis technique, but in comparison to linear technique, it is capable of predicting probability, because the prediction will always lie between 0 and 1, whereas in linear regression it exceeds those limits. Using the logistiv regression we will try to predict what employes might quit the company.

This process starts with specifying the recipe, which includes setting the model where outcome will be attrition and adding training data. Preprocessing steps include:

  • step_novel() to create a specification of a recipe step that will assign a previously unseen factor level to a new value.

  • step_dummy() to create dummy variables from all categorical variables.

  • step_zv() to filter out all numeric variables that have zero variance.

  • step_normalize() to normalize (center and scale) all numeric variables.

The next step would be specifying the model, mode, engine and parameters. As we dont know the exact penalty and mixture parameters, we are using tune function. Penalty parameter controls the amount of regularization and mixture controls the proportion of lasso penalty. The mode is classification, as the predictor is a factor, not a number, and glmnet engine. For logistic regression there are two possible engines that can be used in this research scenario, glm and glmnet. Glmnet has advantages when there are many features and little observation. As our data set is fairly small, we will be using glmnet as an engine.

After that, the workflow is set. It puts together the recipe and model specifications. As a separate step we have to specify the models grid, so when the model is tuning, the sequence of parameters values are used in different models. In the next stage we will determine what parameters and which model turned out to be most accurate.

glmnet_recipe <- 
  recipe(formula = attrition ~ ., data = train) %>% 
  step_novel(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes()) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes()) %>% 
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_predictors(), -all_nominal()) 
 
glmnet_spec <- 
  logistic_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet") 

glmnet_workflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(glmnet_recipe) %>% 
  add_model(glmnet_spec) 

glmnet_grid <- tidyr::crossing(penalty = 10^seq(-6, -1, length.out = 20), mixture = c(0.05, 
    0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1)) 

glmnet_tune <- 
  tune_grid(glmnet_workflow, resamples = folds, grid = glmnet_grid, metrics = metric_set(accuracy, roc_auc))

Building random forest model

In this step we will build a random forest model. Random forest models work by collecting the predictions that were made by multiple decision trees. The first step would be creating a recipe for the mode, just like before attrition will be the outcome and we will be using train data set. The second step would be specifying the model mode and engines. As attrition is a categorical value, the model mode will be classification and engine used for this model will be ranger. When we set the model, some parameters like like mtry (number of predictors that will be randomly sampled at each split when creating the tree models) or min_n (the minimum number of data points in a node that are required for the node to be split further) can be adjusted to optimize their performance. For that we will use tune function. When model is finalized, best values for mtry and min_n will be reflected in the fitted model. Then, in the workflow we connect both recipe and model specification. The last step in this section would be tuning the model. For that, previously created workflow is used, data resamples are added and the number of grids is picked. In this scenario we picked 11 grids.

ranger_recipe <- 
  recipe(formula = attrition ~ ., data = train)

ranger_spec <- 
  rand_forest(mtry = tune(), min_n = tune(), trees = 1000) %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("ranger")

ranger_workflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(ranger_recipe) %>% 
  add_model(ranger_spec)

set.seed(1234)
doParallel::registerDoParallel()
ranger_tune <-
  tune_grid(ranger_workflow, resamples = folds, grid = 11, metrics = metric_set(accuracy, roc_auc))

Random forest model

In this step we are applying the workflow with the final version of model parameters to an actual data set. As a result, a confusion matrix is set, where we can see the exact number of wrong and right predictions.

  # fit on the training set and evaluate on test set

Comparison

As the results show, our linear regression model outperform random forest with 86% accuracy.

Lets also do an unsupervised model

Clustering model - K Means

Aim to answer our sub question 4: Clustering the employees based on attrition. What kind of employees burn out?

For clustering, separate data frame was created that only includes numeric variables and only people who decided to quit their job. By doing that, we can determine patterns among those who decided not to stay at the IBM. For us to build this model we need data frame that consists of numeric variables and a number of clusters that will be set. To find the most suitable and efficient number of cluster several methods can be used.

Now we are building the model using kmeans function, specifying the number of clusters and how many random sets should be chosen in n start.

data_yes <- data_attrition_yes %>%
  select(monthly_income, job_level, age, years_since_last_promotion, distance_from_home)

k3 <- kmeans(data_yes, centers = 3, nstart = 10)

data_attrition_no %>%
  mutate(job_level = case_when(job_level == 1 ~ 1, job_level == 2 ~ 3, job_level == 3 ~ 3, job_level == 4 ~ 4, job_level == 5 ~ 4)) %>%
  group_by(job_level) %>%
  summarise(m = mean(monthly_income),
            d = mean(distance_from_home),
            p = mean(years_since_last_promotion),
            a = mean(age))

Two clusters have sizes of 173, 10 and 54. We can also see the cluster centers or means for the two clusters across 5 variables. The average monthly income for the first cluster is equal to 2973.520 and 16451.200 for the second cluster and 8437.222 for the third group. There is also a 7 year difference in age between the three clusters, with second cluster having older employees and 1 the youngest. In the first category average years since last promotion is only 1 years, while it is 7 years for the second category and 3 for the third.

data_yes %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  mutate(cluster = k3$cluster) %>%
  ggplot(aes(age, monthly_income, color = factor(cluster))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(y = "Monthly income", x = "Age", legend = "Cluster", title = "Clusters")

In conclusion, k-means is a very fast and easy algorithm to use for clustering. However, there are some downsides to using it. First of all it requires to specify the number of clusters. And different methods of choosing the amount of clusters might show different results. Second disadvantage of the k-means is that it is very sensitive to outlines. And third one is that the result can change if we change the order of the data (Kassambara 2017).
